'''The Tengyō Rebellion of the Dewa Fusho''' (天慶の出羽俘囚の乱, Tengyō no Dewa Fushū no Ran) was a rebellion by the {{ill|Fushū|ja|俘囚|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fushū|qq=}} (assimilated Emishi) during the [[:en:Heian period|Heian period]]. It is also referred to as the "Rebellion of the Dewa Fusho," the "Fushū Rebellion," or the "Tengyō Rebellion."
== Events == On {{nihongo|April 17, Tengyō 2|天慶2nd year 4月17日|May 22, 939}}, a rebellion by the fushū occurred, engaging with the garrison at [[:en:Akita Castle|Akita Castle]]. This event was reported to the [[:en:Heian-kyō|Capital of Heian-kyō]] as noted in historical records such as the [[:en:Nihon Kiryaku|Nihon Kiryaku]]. On the following day, three imperial decrees were issued, instructing the training of elite soldiers, fortification of strategic locations, mobilization of vagrants regardless of status, and the ritual appeasement of {{ill|Ōmonoimi no Kami|ja|大物忌神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōmonoimi no Kami|qq=}}, as the oracle predicted that the [[:en:Mount Chōkai|Mount Chōkai]] would burn. According to an excerpt from the {{ill|Teishinkōki|ja|貞信公記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Teishinkōki|qq=}}, the rebels reached [[:en:Akita District|Akita District]], plundering government rice stores. The same record mentions that the rebels were accompanied by "異類" (irui, "other kinds"), which various interpretations suggest might refer to other Emishi groups<ref>Akira Sekiguchi, 1992</ref>, the {{ill|Watari-shima|ja|渡島|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Watari-shima|qq=}} (ancestors of the Ainu)<ref>Ryōsuke Kumada, 2001</ref>, or even early [[:en:Ainu people|Ainu people]].<ref>Takashi Takahashi, 1986</ref>
On {{nihongo|June 21|6月21日|July 24, 939}}, it was reported that troops from {{ill|Mutsu Province|1=Mutsu Province|2=ja|3=陸奥国|ja|Mutsu Province|1=Mutsu Province|2=ja|3=陸奥国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mutsu Province|qq=}} would be relocated. On {{nihongo|July 18|7月18日|August 19, 939}}, two additional decrees were sent to [[:en:Dewa Province|Dewa Province]]. These instructed that weapons and armor stored in the provincial treasury be distributed to soldiers, that grain taxes be used as rations, that troops be trained to suppress the rebellion, and that [[:en:Akita Castle|Akita Castle]] Governor {{ill|Minamoto no Yoshinari|ja|源嘉生|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minamoto no Yoshinari|qq=}} be reprimanded.<ref>[[:en:Honchō Seiki|Honchō Seiki]]</ref>
However, further historical records of the rebellion cease, and the subsequent course of the conflict remains unclear.
